processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Level 1 Minimal Processing has been conducted to establish basic intellectual and physical control of the material and assess immediate preservation and conservation needs. Material remains as received, primarily in original folders and record storage cartons.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Bronk personal and professional papers are arranged partially chronologically, and partially by subject.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: See also: FA220 Rockefeller University records, Executive Assistant, Mabel Bright.
Mabel Bright served as executive assistant to Detlev W. Bronk at Rockefeller University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Includes administrative files; Bronk family history; organizational (national and International) activities; personal and professional correspondence; published clippings; research notes, papers, printed material, photos, graphs; speaking engagements.
The majority of the collection concerns Bronk's personal and professional papers as he served as:
1. 1921-1929 Asst. Prof., Assoc. Prof., Professor, Dean of Men, Swarthmore College.
2. 1929-1948 Professor of Biophysics and Director of the Eldridge Reeves Johnson Foundation for Medical Physics at the University of Pennsylvania.
3. 1936-1948 Director, Institute of Neurology at the University of Pennsylvania.
4. 1940-1941 Professor of Physiology at the Medical College of Cornell University.
5. 1948-1953 President of Johns Hopkins University.
6. 1952 President, American Association for Advancement of Science.
7. 1953-1969 President of the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research (The Rockefeller University).
8. 1950-1962 President of The National Academy of Sciences.

In addition to work performed in these major administrative positions, the Bronk Papers contain files that were created as Bronk served on a host of national and international scientific organizations such as The National Science Foundation, National Research Council, Office of Scientific Research and Development, New York State Science and Technology Foundation, UNESCO, The Royal Society, International Council of Scientific Unions, and the Organization of American States.

Published articles, lectures and personal notes show the wide scope of Bronk's research activities. Addresses and records of speaking engagements evince Bronk's reach into the academic and scientific world community.

3.5 cubic feet of published clippings have been photocopied for research usage. Includes memorabilia such as awards, medals and honorary degrees. Family genealogies and histories enlarge understanding of Bronk's personal orientation.

During World War II Bronk was appointed Coordinator of Research, Office of the Air Surgeon, U.S. Army Air Forces (1942-1946). Numerous files show Bronk's interest and contributions to aviation medicine.

The collection contains many published and unpublished manuscripts Bronk received as editor of various publications, i.e. American Journal of Physiology (1938-1943), Aviation Physiologists Bulletin (1943-1946), Journal of General Physiology (1954-1968).

Bronk was appointed a member of the Advisory Committee to President Dwight D. Eisenhower on Science and Space. In 1958, as President of The National Academy of Science, he organized the Space Science Board, a board designated to study future space vehicles. Records and research studies of projected space programs are found in the files.

The Bronk Papers demonstrate Bronk's extensive acquaintance, friendship and scientific work with scientists and educators. A sampling of correspondents include E.D. Adrian, Frank Brink, Leslie A. Chambers, Britton Chance, H.K. Hartline, E. Newton Hervey, A.V. Hill, M.G. Larrabee, Glenn Millikan, and Arthur J. Rawson.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: Material is open for scholarly research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Material in the Rockefeller family collections that provides the names, correspondence, or activities of living members of the Rockefeller family, and/or documents the net wealth of any Rockefeller family members, is restricted. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.
